com.infinitydb.map.visitor

Class MapVisitor<K,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.infinitydb.map.visitor.MapVisitor<K,V>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - Key of the Map for this step. Keys arrive in visit() in ascending order if the map is ordered and isOrdered = true.
    V - Value of the Map for the single unique corresponding key
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ThreadedMapVisitor

    public abstract class MapVisitor<K,V>
extends java.lang.Object
    A MapVisitor is like a Java 8 BiConsumer but is for use with Visitables such as VisitableMaps.

    The visit() invokes Visitable.visit(Object, Object) for each Entry in the Map. For speed, the optimized VisitableMap may use the special visit() methods here that have primitive parameters instead of the general visit(Object, Object).

    The standard use of a MapVisitor with any VisitableMap is: 

     map.forEach(mapVisitor);
    but if more control over the scan is desired, a VisitableMap implementer can provide a Visitable, which is kind of scan-only Map. The basic pattern is 
     visitableMap.getVisitable().setXXX(?).forEach(mapVisitor);
    The getVisitable() returns a Visitable, which then delegates back to the VisitableMap that created it but the visitable can be configured by the client.

    The ThreadedMapVisitor subclass of MapVisitor allows parallel scanning. A similar RemoteMapVisitor subclass of ThreadedMapVisitor is in progress.

    A re-used MapVisitor implementation allows a very clear usage like: long sum = new Summer().getSum(visitable);

    The MapVisitor threading technique is much faster in practice in certain VisitableMap implementations, especially AirConcurrentMap (and in the future possibly 'NitroMap' and 'OxyMap'). This is true partially because there is only one call to visit(key,value) per Entry rather than two as in an Iterator, and there is very little GC load. The normal java.util.Map#forEach() default implementation in the Map interface uses the entrySet(), which may construct an Entry on each iteration. There are many reasons why that fact affects the speed, which can be significantly higher including inlining opportunities for the JIT.

    Throwing an exception inside visit) terminates the execution and throws the exception into the original invoker of any of the visit methods on the VisitableMap even in the parallel or remote case.

    There is an optional technique for speed when primitive keys or values are being used. There are special possible optimization methods that resemble #visit(Object,Object) but which have primitive parameters and which can be ignored in non-performance-intensive situations. The defaults of these primitive parameter methods delegate to visit(K, V) by constructing primitive wrapper objects. If the VisitableMap wishes to and it is in fact already generating the keys or values as primitives, it may choose to use the visit methods with primitive parameters to improve speed, hoping that the MapVisitor code has overridden the corresponding methods such that there is no usage of Objects at all. This is an optional technique. The regular visit(Object, Object) must be implemented as well because it is abstract, but this is good because it provides broad coverage of input types with high performance as well when possible. For example, the value parameter might be a Number and Number.longValue() would be used for breadth (it converts also double and float), with the MapVisitor#visit(Object, long) being used when possible.

    We have avoided the overload proliferation that would be generated by having methods for all combinations of primitive and Object types for keys and values. The selection we provided depends to some degree on the actual performance characteristics of the primitive types on current processors, but they have very similar characteristics. In some other parallel computing frameworks this proliferation extends not only to a few methods like this but also to many other classes like BiFunctions and so on forming a cross product. We also assume that keys will only be Objects or longs for these special methods. We provide only:

    |{long,Object}*{long,double,float,boolean,Object}|=10 methods

    instead of:

    |{char, byte, short, long, double, float, boolean, Object}|^2=64 methods.

    Note that all primitive integral types including char can be handled quickly as longs, since modern 64-bit processors transfer data in 64-bit units anyway, so for example a byte takes the same time to transfer as a long. There can be small sign and zero extension instructions also that take non-zero time, however. Floats and doubles are handled separately to avoid loss of precision in conversions (even widening ones!), even though the performance improvement is much less.

    It is probably always best for the VisitableMap just to be lazy and avoid converting a key or value to a primitive type from an Object just to get speed, because the MapVisitor's primitive method may then default to a construction and an invocation of visit(Object, Object), anyway which is slower. Just let the Visitor do a Long.longValue() for example if it wants. So a Map containing Object keys and int values internally would normally invoke MapVisitor#visit(Object, long).

    The Visitable idea is actually rather general: the obvious Visitable for a List is below. This Visitable allows any List to be used with any MapVisitor for cross-product generality and re-usability with no GC load for constructed Entries and almost entirely in-lineable method invocation. The MapVisitor can optionally handle long keys explicitly to help to avoid a default construction of a Key and the List should be indexable efficiently, but almost always, the JIT will turn the key construction and longValue() pair into a simple passing of a long. This class is already provided in this system, but it will eventually acquire threading and possibly remoteness. 

     public class VisitableListWrapper<K, V> extends Visitable<K, V> {
     final List<V> list;
 
     VisitableListWrapper(List<V> list) {
         this.list = list;
     }
 
     public void visit(MapVisitor< ? super K, ? super V> visitor) {
         int size = list.size(); // keep in a local for speed
         for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
             visitor.visit(i, list.get(i));
         }
     }
 }
    The issue of fail-fast is separate from the issue of performance. It can be handled easily with generics.

    The issue of the internal representation of the data in the Map is also separate, so the Map can have an internal representation of the keys or values as ints or packed bits for example to save time or space or both. Even composite packed values, Zip-compressed values, and so on are possible because the internal representation is decoupled from the performance optimization.

    The future RemoteMapVisitor extension may add functionality to distribute visiting over a cluster by using ObjectOutputStream/ObjectInputStream or a custom serialization interface. Scheduling and other hints to the cluster can be provided by the visitors themselves before or during the visitation.

      • visit

        public abstract void visit(K key,
                           V value)
        Called once per Entry in the Map. No other methods need to be overridden as they all delegate to this one. It is convenient to implement a very general-purpose method here, and then override the others as desired if that will increase speed. There is no other flavor - it is not different for keys, entries, or values. Thus there is no need for Map.keySet(), Map.entrySet() and Map.values() etc.
        Parameters:
        key - the key in a given Entry at a point int the scan.
        value - corresponds to the single unique key

      • visit

        public void visit(long key,
                  V value)
        The default implementation simply delegates to visit(K, V). If the Visitable wishes to and it is in fact generating primitive keys or values, it may use this method, which may be overridden, to improve speed. Defaults to: 
         visit((K)new Long(key), value);
        Parameters:
        key - the key in a given Entry at a point int the scan.
        value - corresponds to the single unique key
